Girls and fun and good food

272
00:16:19,729 --> 00:16:22,767
and sense of health and purpose...

273
00:16:22,899 --> 00:16:24,731
It can't get better than this.

274
00:16:24,901 --> 00:16:28,235
Nothing in life
could be better than this.

275
00:16:29,071 --> 00:16:32,360
I was always making jokes and teasing,

276
00:16:32,492 --> 00:16:35,860
playing practical jokes on everybody.

277
00:16:48,174 --> 00:16:50,507
To be able to have money.

278
00:16:50,635 --> 00:16:52,001
I never had any money.

279
00:16:53,429 --> 00:16:55,842
My father was a traveling salesman.

280
00:16:56,516 --> 00:16:59,805
I was making more in six months of work

281
00:16:59,936 --> 00:17:01,677
than he made in ten years.

282
00:17:01,812 --> 00:17:04,429
He measured everything by money.

283
00:17:04,565 --> 00:17:07,729
He couldn't understand
how this ne'er-do-well son of his

284
00:17:07,860 --> 00:17:09,522
could possibly do that.

285
00:17:13,157 --> 00:17:15,114
If I have a scene to play

286
00:17:15,243 --> 00:17:16,654
and I have to be angry,

287
00:17:16,786 --> 00:17:20,575
there must be within you trigger
mechanisms that are spring-loaded,

288
00:17:20,706 --> 00:17:24,199
that are filled with contempt
about something.

289
00:17:24,377 --> 00:17:27,290
I remember my father hitting my mother.

290
00:17:27,463 --> 00:17:28,795
I was fourteen.

291
00:17:34,595 --> 00:17:37,554
Now that's how
I'm gonna clear the table.

292
00:17:38,474 --> 00:17:41,717
Don't you ever talk that way to me.

293
00:17:42,728 --> 00:17:45,266
My old man was tough.

294
00:17:45,398 --> 00:17:46,809
He was a bar fighter.

295
00:17:46,941 --> 00:17:49,809
He was a man with not much love in him.

296
00:17:50,987 --> 00:17:52,478
Staying away from home,

297
00:17:52,613 --> 00:17:55,822
drinking and whoring
all around the Midwest.

298
00:17:56,826 --> 00:17:58,442
He used to slap me around,

299
00:17:58,578 --> 00:18:00,240
and for no good reason.

300
00:18:00,371 --> 00:18:03,785
And I was truly intimidated by him
at that time.

301
00:18:03,958 --> 00:18:06,325
Now what kind of a queen
do you think you are?

302
00:18:06,460 --> 00:18:08,543
You know that I've been onto you
from the start,

303
00:18:08,671 --> 00:18:11,789
and not once did you pull the wool
over this boy's eyes.

304
00:18:11,924 --> 00:18:14,667
When things
are extremely painful to you,

305
00:18:14,802 --> 00:18:16,794
you don't want them
in your consciousness,

306
00:18:16,929 --> 00:18:18,795
you want to forget about them.

307
00:18:18,931 --> 00:18:20,388
And you are the Queen of the Nile,

308
00:18:20,516 --> 00:18:22,599
sitting on your throne,
swilling down my liquor.

309
00:18:22,727 --> 00:18:25,686
You know what I say? Ha-ha!

310
00:18:25,855 --> 00:18:29,394
You can imagine
having to go someplace every night

311
00:18:29,525 --> 00:18:30,811
and go through all that,

312
00:18:30,985 --> 00:18:32,442
get yourself upset...

313
00:18:32,570 --> 00:18:34,778
To have to cry or to scream

314
00:18:34,905 --> 00:18:38,694
or to be ruined in some way,
that's work.

315
00:18:38,826 --> 00:18:41,113
That's hard work.

316
00:18:41,245 --> 00:18:43,988
People invariably associated me
with the part I played,

317
00:18:44,165 --> 00:18:47,624
so that it was difficult to believe
that I didn't eat off the floor,

318
00:18:47,752 --> 00:18:52,463
or that I, you know, didn't run up
the street with my shoes off,

319
00:18:52,590 --> 00:18:56,004
and so it's been a hard thing
sort of living that down.

320
00:18:56,844 --> 00:19:00,428
There is nothing about me
that is like Stanley Kowalski.

321
00:19:00,556 --> 00:19:01,922
I hate that kinda guy.

322
00:19:02,058 --> 00:19:03,799
I absolutely hate that person

323
00:19:03,934 --> 00:19:06,221
and I couldn't identify with it.

324
00:19:06,771 --> 00:19:12,233
The brute, dark character that
represented the beasts and the animals.

325
00:19:13,653 --> 00:19:15,986
They sent me to a psychiatrist.

326
00:19:16,989 --> 00:19:18,855
They thought I was going nuts,

327
00:19:19,033 --> 00:19:21,275
losing my mind.

328
00:19:21,410 --> 00:19:23,527
Stella told me,
if you come to the theater

329
00:19:23,663 --> 00:19:26,781
and you feel a hundred percent,
show eighty.

330
00:19:26,916 --> 00:19:30,705
If you come and you feel sixty percent,
show forty.

331
00:19:31,629 --> 00:19:33,165
If you come to the theater

332
00:19:33,297 --> 00:19:35,459
and you only feel forty percent,

333
00:19:35,591 --> 00:19:37,833
best to turn around and go home.

334
00:19:37,968 --> 00:19:40,176
I was wondering if you have any plans

335
00:19:40,304 --> 00:19:42,591
to return to the stage
in the near future.

336
00:19:42,723 --> 00:19:48,560
No, I don't have any immediate
intentions of returning to the stage.

337
00:19:59,031 --> 00:20:00,988
The shouts of freedom

338
00:20:01,117 --> 00:20:03,575
are also the rattling of chains.

339
00:20:05,621 --> 00:20:09,456
You seem to be such a restless man.

340
00:20:09,583 --> 00:20:11,870
Eyes always darting.

341
00:20:12,002 --> 00:20:13,209
I don't know,

342
00:20:13,337 --> 00:20:16,125
I guess I've just got loose feet.

343
00:20:16,757 --> 00:20:22,503
I infer from that that you
do not thoroughly enjoy your profession.

344
00:20:22,680 --> 00:20:24,467
Or you don't enjoy it at all.

345
00:20:24,598 --> 00:20:26,931
No, I think that people
do what they enjoy,

346
00:20:27,059 --> 00:20:28,266
or else they don't do it.

347
00:20:28,394 --> 00:20:30,351
People do what they want to do.

348
00:20:31,230 --> 00:20:34,394
If there are adverse conditions
that surround my work,

349
00:20:34,525 --> 00:20:36,141
they are not adverse enough

350
00:20:36,318 --> 00:20:38,901
to make me change activities.

351
00:20:41,824 --> 00:20:44,737
If I hadn't had the good luck
to be an actor,

352
00:20:44,869 --> 00:20:47,828
I don't know what I would've been.

353
00:20:47,955 --> 00:20:49,867
I'd have probably been a con man.

354
00:20:50,750 --> 00:20:52,582
A good con man.

355
00:20:52,710 --> 00:20:57,171
Tell smooth lies, give impressions
of things that he thinks,

356
00:20:57,339 --> 00:21:00,423
or appears to think
that he doesn't think.

357
00:21:01,260 --> 00:21:02,967
Since I don't do anything else well,

358
00:21:03,095 --> 00:21:05,462
and up to this time I haven't decided

359
00:21:05,598 --> 00:21:06,930
what else I would like to do,

360
00:21:07,057 --> 00:21:08,844
I might as well put all my energies

361
00:21:08,976 --> 00:21:11,389
into being as good an actor as I can.

362
00:21:14,064 --> 00:21:15,771
Now will you turn your head for us?

363
00:21:15,900 --> 00:21:17,107
Sure.

364
00:21:18,486 --> 00:21:20,193
Now around the other way.

365
00:21:22,698 --> 00:21:24,815
Now all the way around.

366
00:21:29,497 --> 00:21:34,162
All right. Thank you and stay around.

367
00:21:36,212 --> 00:21:37,669
Shakespeare said,

368
00:21:37,797 --> 00:21:39,459
"There is no art to find

369
00:21:39,590 --> 00:21:41,707
the mind's construction in the face."

370
00:21:41,842 --> 00:21:44,425
And there should be such an art.

371
00:21:46,055 --> 00:21:48,843
When the camera is close on you,

372
00:21:48,974 --> 00:21:51,762
your face becomes the stage.

373
00:21:51,894 --> 00:21:54,511
Your face is the proscenium arch

374
00:21:54,647 --> 00:21:56,889
of the theater, thirty feet high.

375
00:21:57,817 --> 00:21:59,934
And it sees all the little movements

376
00:22:00,069 --> 00:22:03,483
of the face and the eye and the mouth.

377
00:22:03,614 --> 00:22:06,197
You have the intensity to act.

378
00:22:09,203 --> 00:22:10,319
I wanted very much

379
00:22:10,454 --> 00:22:13,367
to be involved in motion pictures,

380
00:22:13,499 --> 00:22:15,035
so I could change it

381
00:22:15,209 --> 00:22:17,451
into something nearer the truth.

382
00:22:17,586 --> 00:22:20,203
And I was convinced
that I could do that.

383
00:22:21,841 --> 00:22:23,798
About my playing the tuba...

384
00:22:23,926 --> 00:22:26,259
Seems like a lot of fuss
has been made about that.

385
00:22:26,428 --> 00:22:28,090
In the '30s and '40s

386
00:22:28,222 --> 00:22:30,635
you had a particular kind of acting.

387
00:22:30,766 --> 00:22:33,053
You knew who you were gonna get

388
00:22:33,185 --> 00:22:35,017
when you went to the movies.

389
00:22:35,688 --> 00:22:37,975
Gary Cooper oats.

390
00:22:38,148 --> 00:22:39,810
Shredded Wheat Bogart.

391
00:22:39,942 --> 00:22:43,401
Clark Gable Crunchy Fruit Loops.

392
00:22:43,529 --> 00:22:45,270
They were just like breakfast cereals.

393
00:22:45,489 --> 00:22:47,401
The same in every role.

394
00:22:49,118 --> 00:22:52,111
Gestures of anguish and despair,

395
00:22:52,246 --> 00:22:55,205
and that kind of acting became absurd.

396
00:22:58,460 --> 00:23:00,372
The astounding thing

397
00:23:00,504 --> 00:23:01,915
most people don't realize.

398
00:23:02,089 --> 00:23:04,672
All motion pictures today,

399
00:23:04,800 --> 00:23:06,257
all acting today,

400
00:23:06,427 --> 00:23:08,510
stems from Stella Adler.

401
00:23:09,430 --> 00:23:12,138
Stella, so much
has been talked about Method acting.

402
00:23:12,266 --> 00:23:14,098
What exactly is the Method?

403
00:23:14,226 --> 00:23:17,810
All right, let's start at the beginning.

404
00:23:17,938 --> 00:23:20,271
Stella went to Paris

405
00:23:20,441 --> 00:23:23,775
and studied
with Konstantin Stanislavsky,

406
00:23:23,903 --> 00:23:25,314
the great Russian teacher,

407
00:23:25,487 --> 00:23:28,230
brought back
her experience and knowledge

408
00:23:28,407 --> 00:23:30,444
of this particular form of acting.

409
00:23:30,576 --> 00:23:35,321
Reality, realness, carried by an actor

410
00:23:35,539 --> 00:23:37,326
to achieve the truth.

411
00:23:37,499 --> 00:23:39,957
This is the most modern technique.

412
00:23:40,920 --> 00:23:42,411
Everything that you do,

413
00:23:42,546 --> 00:23:43,787
make it real as you can.

414
00:23:43,923 --> 00:23:46,165
Make it alive, make it tangible,

415
00:23:46,300 --> 00:23:48,667
find the truth of that moment.

416
00:23:48,802 --> 00:23:51,169
Mr Stanislavsky understood that.

417
00:23:51,764 --> 00:23:55,303
And the style of acting
changed completely.

418
00:23:56,727 --> 00:23:59,515
The first movie I ever did
was called <i>The Men.</i>

419
00:23:59,647 --> 00:24:01,354
I played a paraplegic

420
00:24:01,565 --> 00:24:04,933
and lived in a hospital
with paraplegics for three weeks.

421
00:24:06,946 --> 00:24:08,733
Physicality is a tough thing.

422
00:24:08,906 --> 00:24:12,820
I spent a lot of time just studying
everything they do.

423
00:24:12,952 --> 00:24:15,990
I wanted to see how
they got in and out of their chairs.

424
00:24:16,163 --> 00:24:19,156
The manner in which you crawled
from one place to another.

425
00:24:20,584 --> 00:24:23,827
Paraplegics,
they do the most amazing things.

426
00:24:23,963 --> 00:24:26,205
Races without their chairs,

427
00:24:26,340 --> 00:24:28,081
I've seen guys walk on their hands.

428
00:24:28,217 --> 00:24:29,628
They can do one-armed pull-ups,

429
00:24:29,802 --> 00:24:31,043
they can do everything.

430
00:24:31,178 --> 00:24:32,840
You have to know your subject,

431
00:24:32,972 --> 00:24:34,588
you have to know your character.

432
00:24:34,723 --> 00:24:37,761
Putting yourself
in a different state of mind.

433
00:24:38,560 --> 00:24:39,846
What they felt like,

434
00:24:39,979 --> 00:24:41,390
what their frustrations were

435
00:24:41,563 --> 00:24:43,805
knowing that they couldn't have sex.

436
00:24:43,941 --> 00:24:46,399
What am I gonna do, where am I gonna go?

437
00:24:47,486 --> 00:24:49,523
I can't go out there anymore.

438
00:24:50,114 --> 00:24:54,028
He just sits there
and he marinates his mind.

439
00:24:54,159 --> 00:24:56,947
In the intellect; That's all he's got.

440
00:24:57,079 --> 00:24:58,365
Put your heart into it.

441
00:24:58,539 --> 00:25:00,701
Get yourself up emotionally.

442
00:25:01,667 --> 00:25:03,704
At night I think about it,

443
00:25:03,836 --> 00:25:05,043
dream about it

444
00:25:05,212 --> 00:25:07,829
and I wake up being absorbed by it.

445
00:25:07,965 --> 00:25:09,672
People have routines:

446
00:25:09,800 --> 00:25:12,668
Acting routines, dancing routines,
painting routines.

447
00:25:12,803 --> 00:25:15,136
The same thing over and over again.

448
00:25:15,264 --> 00:25:17,677
Everything is a cliché.

449
00:25:18,225 --> 00:25:21,844
When an actor takes a little too long
as he's walking to the door,

450
00:25:21,979 --> 00:25:24,141
you know he's going to stop
and turn around and say...

451
00:25:24,273 --> 00:25:27,141
"Frankly, my dear, I don't give a damn."

452
00:25:27,276 --> 00:25:29,438
Jersey Joe Walcott, terrific fighter.

453
00:25:29,611 --> 00:25:33,195
He'd be boxing, he'd be throwing
some punches and bing!

454
00:25:33,365 --> 00:25:35,402
He'd have his fist in somebody's face.

455
00:25:35,576 --> 00:25:37,442
You'd think it was coming out
of the southwest

456
00:25:37,619 --> 00:25:39,451
and there it comes out of the northeast.

457
00:25:39,663 --> 00:25:42,531
He would never let you know
where he was going to hit you.

458
00:25:42,708 --> 00:25:43,949
You.

459
00:25:44,084 --> 00:25:47,919
Never let the audience know
how it's gonna come out.

460
00:25:48,047 --> 00:25:49,047
What is your name?

461
00:25:49,173 --> 00:25:51,085
Get them on your time.

462
00:25:51,216 --> 00:25:55,426
Emiliano Zapata.

463
00:25:59,016 --> 00:26:01,349
And when that time comes
and everything is right,

464
00:26:01,560 --> 00:26:03,893
you just fuck, let fly.

465
00:26:04,021 --> 00:26:07,310
O judgment, thou art fled
to brutish beasts,

466
00:26:07,441 --> 00:26:09,228
and men have lost their reason.

467
00:26:09,359 --> 00:26:10,895
Hit them, knock them over.

468
00:26:11,028 --> 00:26:13,145
With an attitude,

469
00:26:13,280 --> 00:26:14,942
with a word, with a look.

470
00:26:15,699 --> 00:26:17,315
I don't like cops.

471
00:26:17,451 --> 00:26:18,658
Be surprising.

472
00:26:18,786 --> 00:26:21,324
Figure out a way to do it

473
00:26:21,455 --> 00:26:22,946
that has never been done before.

474
00:26:23,082 --> 00:26:24,618
You gotta put something down,

475
00:26:24,750 --> 00:26:25,786
you gotta make some jive.

476
00:26:25,918 --> 00:26:27,705
Don't you know what I'm talking about?

477
00:26:27,836 --> 00:26:31,796
You want to stop that movement
from the popcorn to the mouth.

478
00:26:31,924 --> 00:26:37,670
Cry "Havoc,"
and let slip the dogs of war.

479
00:26:37,805 --> 00:26:39,592
Get people to stop chewing.

480
00:26:39,723 --> 00:26:44,468
That this foul deed
shall smell above the earth.

481
00:26:44,645 --> 00:26:46,682
The truth will do that.

482
00:26:48,023 --> 00:26:50,686
Damn, damn, damn, damn.

483
00:26:50,818 --> 00:26:52,400
When it's right, it's right.

484
00:26:52,611 --> 00:26:54,102
You can feel it in your bones.

485
00:26:55,447 --> 00:26:56,904
Then you feel whole,

486
00:26:57,032 --> 00:26:58,489
then you feel good.

487
00:27:01,870 --> 00:27:03,406
It was pre-sixties.

488
00:27:03,539 --> 00:27:05,656
People were looking for rebellion,

489
00:27:05,791 --> 00:27:08,704
and I happened to be at the right place
at the right time

490
00:27:08,836 --> 00:27:10,702
with the right state of mind.

491
00:27:11,922 --> 00:27:14,881
In a sense, it was my own story.

492
00:27:15,008 --> 00:27:17,466
Rebelling for the sake of rebelling.

493
00:27:35,863 --> 00:27:37,775
Hello, Mr Brando.

494
00:27:37,906 --> 00:27:40,865
I hope you don't think
I'm too crazy for making this recording.

495
00:27:40,993 --> 00:27:42,575
I wrote you a fan letter once,

496
00:27:42,744 --> 00:27:44,451
but I don't know if you received it.

497
00:27:45,956 --> 00:27:49,540
Once I saw a picture of you
with a white cat. Was it yours?

498
00:27:49,710 --> 00:27:53,545
I'll bet you're one of the kindest,
most interesting fellows in Hollywood.

499
00:27:53,714 --> 00:27:55,797
I suppose I'm judging the book
by the cover,

500
00:27:55,924 --> 00:27:58,712
but perhaps I'm not too far wrong.

501
00:27:58,844 --> 00:28:01,712
Mr Brando?
I hope this isn't too personal,

502
00:28:01,847 --> 00:28:05,056
but I always say what I think,
so I won't stop now.

503
00:28:05,184 --> 00:28:07,517
I admire you very much,

504
00:28:07,728 --> 00:28:09,560
both as an actor and a person.

505
00:28:09,771 --> 00:28:12,263
Many, many other people
feel the same way.

506
00:28:12,399 --> 00:28:14,482
I think one of the main reasons
that I admire you

507
00:28:14,610 --> 00:28:16,602
is because you aren't afraid
to be yourself,

508
00:28:16,778 --> 00:28:19,441
instead of being a carbon copy
of everyone else.

509
00:28:19,573 --> 00:28:20,939
It would be a pretty dull world

510
00:28:21,074 --> 00:28:22,815
if everyone behaved in the same way,

511
00:28:22,951 --> 00:28:25,785
so three cheers for you, Mr Brando.

512
00:28:30,584 --> 00:28:34,828
I didn't intend to have
that extraordinary effect.

513
00:28:34,963 --> 00:28:39,754
I became, very quickly, a cult hero.

514
00:28:51,271 --> 00:28:55,311
And now I know that you're as anxious
as I am to find out what actor

515
00:28:55,442 --> 00:28:59,652
has won the Oscar
for the best performance of this year.

516
00:28:59,863 --> 00:29:01,729
The winner is.

517
00:29:01,907 --> 00:29:04,615
Marlon Brando for <i>On the Waterfront.</i>

518
00:29:08,372 --> 00:29:09,579
Marlon Brando,

519
00:29:09,748 --> 00:29:11,910
an actor of very considerable talent.

520
00:29:12,042 --> 00:29:15,001
The youngest actor
ever honoured in this way.

521
00:29:18,006 --> 00:29:20,123
When I saw the picture finally,

522
00:29:20,259 --> 00:29:21,921
I was so embarrassed,

523
00:29:22,052 --> 00:29:24,419
so disappointed in my performance.

524
00:29:25,305 --> 00:29:28,844
It's much heavier than I imagined.

525
00:29:29,851 --> 00:29:32,810
It's like carrying a monkey around
on your back.

526
00:29:32,938 --> 00:29:36,181
They're asking me to put the finger
on my own brother.

527
00:29:37,359 --> 00:29:41,319
It's a very strange thing
this business of storytelling.

528
00:29:41,488 --> 00:29:43,525
You don't always know when you're good.

